# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alceu-amoroso-lima
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In addition, he founded the Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam, the Anti-Revolutionary Party, and a newspaper.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He vigorously denounced modernism in theology as a fad that would die out.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In politics, he dominated the Anti-Revolutionary Party (ARP) from its founding in 1879 to his death in 1920.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He promoted pillarisation, the social expression of the anti-thesis in public life, whereby Protestant, Catholic and secular elements each had their own independent schools, universities and social organisations.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Abraham Kuyper was born on 29 October 1837 in Maassluis, Netherlands.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] His father Jan Frederik Kuyper served as a minister for the Dutch Reformed Church in Hoogmade, Maassluis, Middelburg and Leiden.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] The boy received no formal primary education, but received secondary education at the Gymnasium of Leiden.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1855, he graduated from the Gymnasium and began to study literature, philosophy and theology at Leiden University.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He received his propaedeuse in literature in 1857, and summa cum laude in philosophy in 1858.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He also took classes in Arabic, Armenian and physics.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In comparing the views of John Calvin and Jan Łaski, Kuyper showed a clear sympathy for the more liberal Łaski.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] During his studies, Kuyper was a member of the modern tendency within the Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In May 1862, he was declared eligible for the ministry, and in 1863, he accepted a call to become minister for the Dutch Reformed Church for the town of Beesd.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In the same year he married Johanna Hendrika Schaay (1842–1899).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1864 he began corresponding with the anti-revolutionary MP Guillaume Groen van Prinsterer, who heavily influenced his political and theological views (see below).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Around 1866, he began to sympathise with the orthodox tendency within the Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He was inspired by the robust reformed faith of Pietje Baltus, a single woman in her early 30s, the daughter of a miller.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He began to oppose the centralization in the church, the role of the King and began to plead for the separation of church and state.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1867, Kuyper was asked to become minister for the parish in Utrecht and he left Beesd.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1870 he was asked to come to Amsterdam.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1871 he began to write for the *De Heraut* (*The Herald*).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1872, he founded his own paper, *De Standaard* (*The Standard*).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] This paper laid the foundation for the network of Reformed organisation (the Reformed pillar), which Kuyper founded.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1886, Kuyper led an exodus from the Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He grieved the loss of Reformed distinctives within the State Church, which no longer required office bearers to agree to the Reformed standards which had once been foundational.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper and the consistory of Amsterdam insisted that both ministers and church members subscribe to the Reformed confessions.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] This was appealed to the classis, and Kuyper, along with about eighty members of the Amsterdam consistory, were suspended in December 1885.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] This was appealed to the provincial synod, which upheld the ruling in a 1 July 1886 ruling.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Refusing to accept his suspension, Kuyper preached to his followers in an auditorium on Sunday, 11 July 1886.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Because of their deep sorrow at the state of the Dutch Reformed Church, the group called itself the *Doleantie* (grieving ones).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] By 1889, the *Doleantie* churches had over 200 congregations, 180,000 members, and about 80 ministers.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper, although at first antagonistic towards them, soon began to seek union with the churches of the Secession of 1834, the *Christelijke Gereformeerde Kerken* (Christian Reformed Church).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] These churches had earlier broken off from the Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] This union was effected in 1892, and the *Gereformeerde Kerken in Nederland* (Reformed Churches in the Netherlands) was formed.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] This denomination has its counterpart in the Christian Reformed Church in North America.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He strongly opposed modernism in theology, viewing it as a new-fangled fad based on a superficial view of reality.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He argued that modernism missed the reality of God, of prayer, of sin, and of the church.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He said modernism would eventually prove as useless as 'A Squeezed Out Lemon Peel,' while traditional religious truths would survive.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In his lectures at Princeton in 1898, he argued that Calvinism was more than theology—it provided a comprehensive worldview and indeed had already proven to be a major positive factor in the development of the institutions and values of modern society.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1873, Kuyper stood as candidate in the general election for parliament for the constituency of Gouda, but he was defeated by the incumbent member of parliament, the conservative Jonkheer Willem Maurits de Brauw (1810–1874).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] When De Brauw died the next year, Kuyper stood again in the by-election for the same district.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] This time he was elected to parliament, defeating the liberal candidate Herman Verners van der Loeff.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper subsequently moved to The Hague, without telling his friends in Amsterdam.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In parliament he showed a particular interest in education, especially the equal financing of public and religious schools.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1876, he wrote "Our Program" which laid the foundation for the Anti-Revolutionary Party.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In this programme he formulated the principle of antithesis, the conflict between the religious (Reformed and Catholics) and non-religious.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] More broadly, this programme articulated his broader political philosophy, emphasizing the proper role of government among the other spheres of life, including the family and the church.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper argued that government's authority, like all human authority, derived from God's authority.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1877, he left parliament because of problems with his health, suffering from overexertion.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1878, Kuyper returned to politics, he led the petition against a new law on education, which would further disadvantage religious schools.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] This was an important impetus for the foundation of the Anti-Revolutionary Party (ARP) in 1879, of which Kuyper was chairman between 1879 and 1905.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He was the undisputed leader of the party between 1879 and 1920.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] His followers gave him the nickname "Abraham de Geweldenaar" (Abraham the Masterful).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1880, he founded the Free University in Amsterdam and he was made professor of Theology there.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He also served as its first rector magnificus.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1881, he also became professor of literature.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1886, he left the Dutch Reformed Church, with a large group of followers.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] The parish in Amsterdam was made independent of the church, and kept their own building.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Between 1886 and 1892, they were called the *Dolerenden* (those with grievances).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1892, those Dolerenden founded a new denomination called The Reformed Churches in the Netherlands after merging with other orthodox Reformed people who had seceded from the Dutch Reformed Church in 1834.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In the general election of 1894, Kuyper was re-elected to the House of Representatives for the district of Sliedrecht.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He defeated the liberal Van Haaften and the anti-takkian anti-revolutionary Beelaerts van Blokland.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He also ran as a candidate in Dordrecht and Amsterdam, but was defeated there.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In the election he joined the so-called Takkians, in a conflict between the liberal minister Tak, and a majority House of Representatives.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Tak wanted to reform the census-suffrage, but a majority in parliament rejected his proposal.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper favoured the legislation because he expected the enfranchised lower class voters would favour his party.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] This orientation towards the lower classes gave him the nickname "The bellringer of the common people" (*klokkenist van de kleine luyden*).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] His position on suffrage also led to a conflict within the ARP: a group around Alexander de Savornin Lohman was opposed on principle to universal suffrage because they rejected popular sovereignty; they left the ARP to found the CHU in 1901.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] The authoritarian leadership of Kuyper also played an important role in this conflict.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Lohman opposed party discipline and wanted MPs to make up their own mind, while Kuyper favoured strong leadership.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] After the elections Kuyper became chair of the parliamentary caucus of the ARP.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In his second term as MP he concentrated on more issues than education, like suffrage, labour, and foreign policy.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In foreign affairs especially the Second Boer War was of particular interest to him, in the conflict between the Dutch-speaking reformed farmers and the English-speaking Anglicans he sided with the Boers, and heavily opposed the English.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1896, Kuyper voted against the new suffrage law of Van Houten, because according to Kuyper the reforms did not go far enough.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In the 1897 elections, Kuyper competed in Zuidhorn, Sliedrecht and Amsterdam.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He was defeated by liberals in Zuidhorn and Amsterdam, but he defeated the liberal Wisboom in Sliedrecht.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In Amsterdam he was defeated by Johannes Tak van Poortvliet.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] As an MP, Kuyper kept his job as journalist, and he even became chair of the Dutch Circle of Journalists in 1898; when he left in 1901 he was made honorary president.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In the same year, at the invitation of B.B.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Warfield, Kuyper delivered the "Stone Lectures" at Princeton Seminary, which was his first widespread exposure to a North American audience.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] These lectures were given 10–11 October 14 and 19–21 in 1898.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He discusses the relationship of Calvinism with philosophy, religion, politics, science, art and the future.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He also received an honorary doctorate in law there.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] During his time in the United States, he also traveled to address several Dutch Reformed congregations in Michigan and Iowa and Presbyterian gatherings in Ohio and New Jersey.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In the 1901 elections, Kuyper was re-elected in Sliedrecht, defeating the liberal De Klerk.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In Amsterdam he was defeated again, now by the freethinking liberal Nolting.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He did not take his seat in parliament however but was instead appointed formateur and later prime minister of the Dutch cabinet.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He also served as minister of Home Affairs.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He originally wanted to become minister of labour and enterprise, but neither Mackay or Heemskerk, prominent anti-revolutionaries, wanted to become minister of Home Affairs, forcing him to take the portfolio.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] During his time as prime minister he showed a strong leadership style: he changed the rules of procedure of cabinet in order to become chair of cabinet for four years (before him, the chairmanship of the cabinet had rotated among its members).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] The portfolio of home affairs at the time was very broad: it involved local government, industrial relations, education and public morality.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] The 1903 railway strike was one of the decisive issues for his cabinet.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper produced several particularly harsh laws to end the strikes (the so-called "worgwetten", strangling laws), and pushed them through parliament.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He also proposed legislation to improve working conditions; however only those on fishing and harbour construction passed through parliament.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In education Kuyper changed several education laws to improve the financial situation of religious schools.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] His law on higher education, which would make the diplomas of faith-based universities equal to that of the public universities, was defeated in the Senate.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Consequently, Kuyper dissolved the Senate and, after a new one was elected, the legislation was accepted.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He was also heavily involved in foreign policy, giving him the nickname "Minister of Foreign Travels".
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1905, his ARP lost the elections and was confined to opposition, a defeat Kuyper later blamed on the ‘disloyalty and apostasy’ of Andries Staalman, who had broken away to form the Christian Democratic Party.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Between 1905 and 1907, Kuyper made a grand tour around the Mediterranean.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1907, Kuyper became honorary doctor at the Delft University of Technology.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1907, he was re-elected chair of the ARP, a post which he held until his death in 1920.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1907, Kuyper wanted to return to parliament.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In a by-election in Sneek he needed the support of the local CHU.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] This led to a personal conflict between Kuyper and De Savorin Lohman.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1908, he came into conflict with Heemskerk, who had not involved him in the formation of the CHU/ARP/Catholic General League cabinet, thereby denying him the chance to return as minister.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1908, Kuyper received the honorary title of minister of state.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He was elected to the House of Representatives for the district of Ommen in the by-elections in the same year, defeating the liberal De Meester.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He also ran in Sneek where he was elected as sole candidate.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1909, he was made chair of the committee that prepared the new orthography of the Dutch language.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In the same year he also received an honorary doctorate at the Catholic University of Leuven.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In the 1909 elections he was re-elected in Ommen, defeating the liberal Teesselink, but he was defeated in Dordrecht by the liberal De Kanter.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1909, he came under heavy criticism in the so-called decorations affairs (*lintjeszaak*).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] While minister of home affairs, Kuyper allegedly received money from one Rudolf Lehman, to make him Officer in the Order of Orange-Nassau.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] A parliamentary debate was held on the subject and a committee was instituted to research the claim.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1910, the committee reported that Kuyper was innocent.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Between 1910 and 1912, he was member of the committee headed by Heemskerk, which prepared a revision of the constitution.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1912, he resigned his seat in parliament for health reasons, but he returned to politics in the following year, this time as a member of the Senate for the province of South Holland.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1913, he was made commander in the Order of the Netherlands Lion.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] During the First World War Kuyper sided with the Germans, because he had opposed the English since the Boer wars.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1918, Kuyper played an important role in the formation of the first cabinet led by Charles Ruijs de Beerenbrouck.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1920, at the age of 83 Kuyper died in The Hague and was buried amid great public attention.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper's theological and political views are linked.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] His orthodox Protestant beliefs heavily influenced his anti-revolutionary politics.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 1905 there was a higher education law enacted, but Kuyper was against this and became part of the opposition.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Theologically Kuyper has also been very influential.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He opposed the liberal tendencies within the Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] This eventually led to secession and the foundation of Reformed Churches in the Netherlands.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He developed the so-called neo-Calvinism, which goes beyond conventional Calvinism on a number of issues.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Furthermore, Kuyper made a significant contribution to the formulation of the principle of common grace in the context of a Calvinist world-view.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Most important has been Kuyper's view on the role of God in everyday life.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He believed that God continually influenced the life of believers, and daily events could show his workings.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] God's acts are necessary to ensure the continued existence of creation.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Without his direct activity, creation would self-destruct.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper's political ideals were orthodox-Protestant and anti-revolutionary.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] The concept of sphere sovereignty was very important for Kuyper.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He rejected the popular sovereignty of France in which all rights originated with the individual, and the state-sovereignty of Germany in which all rights derived from the state.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Instead, he wanted to honour the "intermediate bodies" in society, such as schools and universities, the press, business and industry, the arts etc., each of which would be sovereign in its own sphere.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In the interest of a level playing field, he championed the right of every faith community (among whom he counted humanists and socialists) to operate their own schools, newspapers, hospitals, youth movements etc.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He sought equal government finances for all faith-based institutions.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He saw an important role for the state in upholding the morality of the Dutch people.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He favoured monarchy, and saw the House of Orange as historically and religiously linked to the Dutch people.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] His commitment to universal suffrage was only tactical; he expected the Anti-Revolutionary Party would be able to gain more seats this way.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In actuality, Kuyper wanted a Householder Franchise where fathers of each family would vote for his family.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He also favoured a Senate representing the various interest, vocational and professional groups in society.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] With his ideals, he defended the interests of a group of middle class orthodox reformed, who were often referred to as "the little people" (*de kleine luyden*).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He formulated the principle of antithesis: a divide between secular and religious politics.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Liberals and socialists, who were opposed to mixing religion and politics, were his natural opponents.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Catholics were a natural ally, for not only did they want to practice religiously inspired politics, but they also were no electoral opponent, because they appealed to different religious groups.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Socialists, who preached class conflict, were a danger to the reformed workers.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He called for workers to accept their fates and be happy with a simple life because the afterlife would be much more satisfying and revolution would only lead to instability.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] At the same time, he argued that the system of unrestricted free enterprise was in need of "architectonic critique" and he urged government to adopt labour legislation and to inspect workplaces.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper's political views and acts have influenced Dutch politics.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper stood at the cradle of pillarisation, the social expression of the anti-thesis in public life.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] His championing of parity treatment for faith-based organisations and institutions created the basis for the alliance between Protestants and Catholics that has dominated Dutch politics to the present day.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] One of the major political parties of the Netherlands, the CDA, is still heavily influenced by Kuyper's thought.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] There is still a small federation named the Continued Reformed Churches in the Netherlands which remains loyal to the foundations laid by Kuyper.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In North America, Kuyper's political and theological views have had a significant impact, especially in the Reformed community.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] He is considered the father of Dutch Neo-Calvinism and had considerable influence on the thought of philosopher Herman Dooyeweerd.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Others that have been influenced by Kuyper include Auguste Lecerf, Francis Schaeffer, Cornelius Van Til, Alvin Plantinga, Nicholas Wolterstorff, Albert M.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Wolters, Vincent Bacote, Anthony Bradley, Chuck Colson, Timothy J.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Tudur Jones, Bobi Jones, and the hip-hop artist Lecrae.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] In 2006, Reformed Bible College, located in Grand Rapids, Michigan was renamed in honor of Abraham Kuyper and is now Kuyper College.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] As well as Kuyper's profound influence upon European Christian-Democrat politics up to the present, his political theology was also crucial in the history of South Africa.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] His legacy in South Africa is arguably even greater than within the Netherlands.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] There, his Christian-National conception, centred upon the identification of the Afrikaner Calvinist community as the *kern der natie*, became a rallying position for the Dutch Reformed Church in South Africa.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] As Christian nationalists, Kuyper's adherents in South Africa were instrumental in the building of Afrikaner cultural, political and economic institutions to restore Afrikaner fortunes following the Boer War, which ultimately led to apartheid.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Saul Dubow notes that Kuyper advocated "the commingling of blood" as "the physical basis for all higher development" in the Stone Lectures (1898).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Harinck argues that "Kuyper was not guided by the cultural racism of his day, but by his Calvinistic creed of human equality".
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper's legacy includes a granddaughter, Johtje Vos, who is noted for having sheltered many Jews in her home in the Netherlands from the Nazis.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/abraham-kuyper] After World War II she moved to New York City.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Activism may be performed on a day-to-day basis in a wide variety of ways, including through the creation of art (artivism), computer hacking (hacktivism), or simply in how one chooses to spend their money (economic activism).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] For example, the refusal to buy clothes or other merchandise from a company as a protest against the exploitation of workers by that company could be considered an expression of activism.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] However, the term commonly refers to a form of collective action, in which numerous individuals coordinate an act of protest together.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Collective action that is purposeful, organized, and sustained over a period of time becomes known as a social movement.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Historically, activists have used literature, including pamphlets, tracts, and books to disseminate or propagate their messages and attempt to persuade their readers of the justice of their cause.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Research has now begun to explore how contemporary activist groups use social media to facilitate civic engagement and collective action combining politics with technology.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Left-wing and right-wing online activists often use different tactics.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Hashtag activism and offline protest are more common on the left.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Working strategically with partisan media, migrating to alternative platforms, and manipulation of mainstream media are more common on the right (in the United States).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] In addition, the perception of increased left-wing activism in science and academia may decrease conservative trust in science and motivate some forms of conservative activism, including on college campuses.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Some scholars have also shown how the influence of very wealthy Americans is a form of activism.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Separating activism and terrorism can be difficult and has been described as a 'fine line'.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The *Online Etymology Dictionary* records the English words "activism" and "activist" as in use in the political sense from the year 1920 or 1915 respectively.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The history of the word *activism* traces back to earlier understandings of collective behavior and social action.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] As late as 1969 *activism was* defined as "the policy or practice of doing things with decision and energy", without regard to a political signification, whereas *social action was* defined as "organized action taken by a group to improve social conditions", without regard to normative status.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Following the surge of "new social movements" in the United States during the 1960s, activism came to be understood as a rational and legitimate democratic form of protest or appeal.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] In English history, the Peasants' Revolt erupted in response to the imposition of a poll tax, and has been paralleled by other rebellions and revolutions in Hungary, Russia, and more recently, for example, Hong Kong.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] In 1930 under the leadership of Mahatma Gandhi thousands of protesting Indians participated in the Salt March, as a protest against the oppressive taxes of their government, resulting in the imprisonment of 60,000 people and eventually independence of their nation.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Activism has had major impacts on Western societies as well, particularly over the past century through social movements such as the Labour movement, the women's rights movement, and the civil rights movement.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Activism has often been thought to address either human rights or environmental concerns, but libertarian and religious right activism are also important types.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] In the 21st century, the intersection between human rights and environmentalism has become increasingly important, leading to criticism of the mainstream environmentalist movement and the development of the environmental justice and climate justice movements.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Human rights activism seeks to protect basic rights such as those laid out in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights including such liberties as: right to life, citizenship, and property, freedom of movement; constitutional freedoms of thought, expression, religion, peaceful assembly; and others.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The foundations of the global human rights movement involve resistance to colonialism, imperialism, slavery, racism, segregation, patriarchy, and oppression of indigenous peoples.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Instead, it is between an emergent group (Activists) that fuses *both ideologies* and a less ideological category of 'somewhat conservative' Establishment Republicans." One example of this activism is the Tea Party movement.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Pew Research identified a "group of 'Staunch Conservatives' (11 percent of the electorate) who are strongly religious, across-the-board socially and economically conservative, and more politically active than other groups on the Right.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Activists employ many different methods, or tactics, in pursuit of their goals.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The tactics chosen are significant because they can determine how activists are perceived and what they are capable of accomplishing.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] For example, nonviolent tactics generally tend to garner more public sympathy than violent ones. and are more than twice as effective in achieving stated goals.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Historically, most activism has focused on creating substantive changes in the policy or practice of a government or industry.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Some activists try to persuade people to change their behavior directly (see also direct action), rather than to persuade governments to change laws.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] For example, the cooperative movement seeks to build new institutions which conform to cooperative principles, and generally does not lobby or protest politically.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Other activists try to persuade people or government policy to remain the same, in an effort to counter change.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Greta Thunberg a Swedish climate activist is known for founding the Fridays for Future movement.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Charles Tilly developed the concept of a "repertoire of contention", which describes the full range of tactics available to activists at a given time and place.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] This repertoire consists of all of the tactics which have been proven to be successful by activists in the past, such as boycotts, petitions, marches, and sit-ins, and can be drawn upon by any new activists and social movements.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Activists may also innovate new tactics of protest.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] These may be entirely novel, such as Douglas Schuler's idea of an "activist road trip", or may occur in response to police oppression or countermovement resistance.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] New tactics then spread to others through a social process known as diffusion, and if successful, may become new additions to the activist repertoire.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Activism is not an activity always performed by those who profess activism as a profession.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The term "activist" may apply broadly to anyone who engages in activism, or narrowly limited to those who choose political or social activism as a vocation or characteristic practice.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Helena Alviar Garcia has combined activism with her work as a legal scholar, resulting in academia being seen as activism.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Judges may employ judicial activism to promote their own conception of the social good.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The definition of judicial activism and whether a specific decisions is activist are controversial political issues.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The legal systems of different nations vary in the extent that judicial activism may be permitted.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Activists can also be public watchdogs and whistle blowers by holding government agencies accountable to oversight and transparency.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Political activism may also include political campaigning, lobbying, voting, or petitioning.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Often political activists also publish their ideas themselves via newsletters, periodicals, presses, or digital media.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Political activism does not depend on a specific ideology or national history, as can be seen, for example, in the importance of conservative British women in the 1920s on issues of tariffs.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Political activism, although often identified with young adults, occurs across peoples entire life-courses.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The power of Internet activism came into a global lens with the Arab Spring protests starting in late 2010.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] People living in the Middle East and North African countries that were experiencing revolutions used social networking to communicate information about protests, including videos recorded on smart phones, which put the issues in front of an international audience.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] This was one of the first occasions in which social networking technology was used by citizen-activists to circumvent state-controlled media and communicate directly with the rest of the world.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] These types of practices of Internet activism were later picked up and used by other activists in subsequent mass mobilizations, such as the 15-M Movement in Spain in 2011, Occupy Gezi in Turkey in 2013, and more.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Online "left- and right-wing activists use digital and legacy media differently to achieve political goals".
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Left-wing online activists are usually more involved in traditional "hashtag activism" and offline protest, while right-wing activists may "manipulate legacy media, migrate to alternative platforms, and work strategically with partisan media to spread their messages".
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Research suggests right-wing online activists are more likely to use "strategic disinformation and conspiracy theories".
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Internet activism may also refer to activism which focuses on protecting or changing the Internet itself, also known as digital rights.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The Digital Rights movement consists of activists and organizations, such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation, who work to protect the rights of people in relation to new technologies, particularly concerning the Internet and other information and communications technologies.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Many contemporary activists now utilize new tactics through the Internet and other information and communication technologies (ICTs), also known as Internet activism or cyber-activism.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Some scholars argue that many of these new tactics are digitally analogous to the traditional offline tools of contention.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Other digital tactics may be entire new and unique, such as certain types of hacktivism.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Together they form a new "digital repertoire of contention" alongside the existing offline one.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The rising use of digital tools and platforms by activists has also increasingly led to the creation of decentralized networks of activists that are self-organized and leaderless, or what is known as **franchise activism**.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Economic activism involves using the economic power of government, consumers, and businesses for social and economic policy change.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Both conservative and liberal groups use economic activism as a form of pressure to influence companies and organizations to oppose or support particular political, religious, or social values and behaviors.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] This may be done through ethical consumerism to reinforce "good" behavior and support companies one would like to succeed, or through boycott or divestment to penalize "bad" behavior and pressure companies to change or go out of business.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Brand activism is the type of activism in which business plays a leading role in the processes of social change.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Applying brand activism, businesses show concern for the communities they serve, and their economic, social, and environmental problems, which allows businesses to build sustainable and long-term relationships with the customers and prospects.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Kotler and Sarkar defined the phenomenon as an attempt by firms to solve the global problems its future customers and employees care about.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Consumer activism consists of activism carried out on behalf of consumers for consumer protection or by consumers themselves.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] For instance, activists in the free produce movement of the late 1700s protested against slavery by boycotting goods produced with slave labor.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Today, vegetarianism, veganism, and freeganism are all forms of consumer activism which boycott certain types of products.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Shareholder activism involves shareholders using an equity stake in a corporation to put pressure on its management.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The goals of activist shareholders range from financial (increase of shareholder value through changes in corporate policy, financing structure, cost cutting, etc.) to non-financial (disinvestment from particular countries, adoption of environmentally friendly policies, etc.).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Design activism locates design at the center of promoting social change, raising awareness on social/political issues, or questioning problems associated with mass production and consumerism.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Design Activism is not limited to one type of design.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Art activism or artivism utilizes the medium of visual art as a method of social or political commentary.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Art activism can activate utopian thinking, which is imagining about an ideal society that is different from the current society, which is found to be effective for increasing collective action intentions.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Fashion activism was coined by Celine Semaan.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Fashion activism is a type of activism that ignites awareness by giving consumers tools to support change, specifically in the fashion industry.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] It has been used as an umbrella term for many social and political movements that have taken place in the industry.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Fashion Activism uses a participatory approach to a political activity.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Craft activism or craftivism is a type of visual activism that allows people to bring awareness to political or social discourse.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] It is a creative approach to activism as it allows people to send short and clear messages to society.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] People who contribute to craftivism are called "craftivists".
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Activism in literature may publish written works that express intended or advocated reforms.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Alternatively, literary activism may also seek to reform perceived corruption or entrenched systems of power within the publishing industry.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Science activism may include efforts to better communicate science or advocate for funding of scientific research.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] It may also include efforts to increase perceived legitimacy of particular scientific fields or respond to the politicization of particular fields.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Some forms of science or scholarly activism on political topics can reduce the separation of science from political advocacy and reduce the credibility of science.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The March for Science held around the world in 2017 and 2018 were notable examples of science activism.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Approaches to science activism vary from protests to more psychological, marketing-oriented approaches that takes into account such factors as individual sense of self, aversion to solutions to problems, and social perceptions.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Some groups and organizations participate in activism to such an extent that it can be considered as an industry.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] In these cases, activism is often done full-time, as part of an organization's core business.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Many organizations in the activism industry are either non-profit organizations or non-governmental organizations with specific aims and objectives in mind.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Most activist organizations do not manufacture goods, but rather mobilize personnel to recruit funds and gain media coverage.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] The term *activism industry* has often been used to refer to outsourced fundraising operations.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] However, activist organizations engage in other activities as well.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Lobbying, or the influencing of decisions made by government, is another activist tactic.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Many groups, including law firms, have designated staff assigned specifically for lobbying purposes.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] In the United States, lobbying is regulated by the federal government.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Many government systems encourage public support of non-profit organizations by granting various forms of tax relief for donations to charitable organizations.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/activist] Governments may attempt to deny these benefits to activists by restricting the political activity of tax-exempt organizations.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald was born the son of a farmer in Greußenheim in Lower Franconia and attended primary school there between 1881 and 1888 before completing an apprenticeship as a carpenter in Würzburg.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] From 1900 to 1902, Stegerwald studied economics under Lujo Brentano at the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He began his engagement with the labour movement in 1893, when he joined the Catholic *Gesellenverein*, a non-union Catholic labour society, in Günzburg.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] From 1896, he was part of the workers' electoral association of the Centre Party in Munich, where he was committed to building the burgeoning Catholic trade union movement.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He advanced quickly, becoming honorary chairman of the Central Union of Christian Woodworkers in 1899 and, in 1903, general-secretary of the General Association of German Christian Trade Unions, a position he retained until 1929.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] In his political role, he steered a conservative course, supporting the Empire and its colonial ambitions.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He attempted to unify the non-socialist unions, such as the Protestant DHV and the Catholic *Gesellvereine*, into a unified organisation to create a counterweight to the socialist free trade unions, though he was unsuccessful.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He supported the German war effort in the First World War and served on the board of the Wartime Food Office from 1916 to 1919, as well as in the Prussian House of Lords during the final year of the war.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] In the aftermath of the November Revolution, Stegerwald represented the Catholic trade unions in co-signing the 15 November working agreement between the unions and employers' associations.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] The working agreement set out a common understanding between labour and capital, acknowledging unions as the legitimate representatives of the workers and setting out the basis for collective bargaining agreements and the eight-hour day.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Throughout the following year Stegerwald called for the end to the workers' council movement which was popular among many radical workers, mostly in the socialist unions.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] In 1919, he became head of the German Trade Union Federation (DGB), the reorganised Christian trade union federation.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Initially, it bore a close resemblance to Stegerwald's prewar proposal of a broad non-socialist union federation, including the Catholic unions as well as the liberal Hirsch-Duncker unions and the Protestant white-collar associations.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] However, the more secular Hirsch-Duncker unions departed in November, leaving the DGB largely dominated by the Catholic unions with a deeply conservative Protestant minority in the German National Association of Commercial Employees (DHV).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] As leader of the DGB, Stegerwald struggled to maintain the unity of the federation's conflicting parts.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Left-wing elements such as the Catholic miners' and industrial unions resented Stegerwald's conservative orientation and his continuous attempts to find common cause with conservative Protestants rather than seek better conditions for workers.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] At the same time, he sought constantly to appease the ultraconservative white-collar DHV.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] In 1927, he sided with the DGB's industrial unions in opposing a widely-agreed wage increase for civil servants.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] This effort failed and alienated him from the white-collar elements of the DGB, to whom he had previously been a stalwart ally.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] After becoming chair of the Centre's Reichstag delegation in January 1929, he resigned from his union positions.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He was succeeded as chair of the DGB by Heinrich Imbusch, leader of the miners' union.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald was elected to both the national and Prussian constituent assembles early in 1919, and became minister for public welfare in Prussia under Social Democratic minister-president Paul Hirsch.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] At the DGB congress in 1920, Stegerwald proposed the formation of an inter-denominational "People's Party", through which he hoped to unite both Catholics and Protestants in a conservative project opposed to socialism, liberalism, and materialism.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] The idea was roundly rejected: the right wing of the Centre opposed abandoning their Catholic orientation while the left-wing feared the conservative, anti-labour orientation of such a party.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Nonetheless, Stegerwald remained a convinced advocate of a pan-Christian party for the rest of his life.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] During the government impasse following the 1921 Prussian state election, the state Centre Party drafted Stegerwald to serve as interim Minister-President.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He was tasked with putting together a cabinet including Social Democrats, the Centre, the left-liberal Democrats, and the conservative German People's Party.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He was invested by the Landtag with a large majority in April, but soon came to blows with the Social Democrats, who withdrew their support.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] His cabinet consisted of a minority government of the Centre and Democrats, and negotiations to expand it stalled out toward the end of the year.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] It finally collapsed in October when the Democrats quit in protest against Stegerwald's proposal to hand the interior ministry to the Social Democrats.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He resigned, and in short order a new centre-left government was formed under Social Democrat Otto Braun.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] This proved to be the end of Stegerwald's involvement in Prussian state politics.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald strongly advocated for the Centre to form part of a conservative government in the Reich under Hans Luther, using his role as head of the DGB to claim widespread union support.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] For this he received a cold reception at the October 1924 congress of the DGB's industrial unions and was attacked by Heinrich Imbusch, head of the miners' union.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Ultimately the unions passed a resolution declaring neutrality in political affairs and Stegerwald was forced to walk back his previous statements.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] When the first Luther cabinet was invested the following January, the majority of the labour representatives among the Centre's Reichstag delegation did not support it.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] At the Centre Party congress in November 1925 Stegerwald was heckled by Joseph Wirth, outspoken leader of the Centre left, who accused him of giving a pass to nationalist extremism.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] After the collapse of the Luther cabinet the following year, Stegerwald's perspective on cooperation with the conservative right changed.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He no longer considered the German National People's Party "worthy of carrying Christian spirit in public life", finding the party both anti-Catholic and uninterested in serious advocacy for the Protestant churches or Christian values.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] In December 1928, the Centre Party congress was tasked with electing a new party chairman.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] The executive unanimously recommended Stegerwald.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] This choice was intended to be a fig leaf to the unions and facilitate Stegerwald's movement out of the DGB leadership into full-time politics, which he had long sought.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] However, the party national committee rejected Stegerwald: this was at least in part due to the predominance of civil servants on the committee, whose interests Stegerwald had unexpectedly opposed the previous year.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He was also opposed for reasons of personality as well as his opposition to church interference in the party.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] The party hierarchy considered several alternatives and ultimately put forward three names to a floor vote: Stegerwald, his rival in the unions Joseph Joos, and prelate Ludwig Kaas.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald received 42 votes, Joos 92, and Kaas 182.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Despite this defeat, in January 1929, Stegerwald was elected head of the Centre Reichstag faction.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He resigned his position as head of the DGB and in the unions, finally completing his move to full-time politics.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] In April he became Minister for Transport in the new Great Coalition under Hermann Müller.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] When the government fell in March 1930, Stegerwald was promoted to Labour Minister by new Chancellor Heinrich Brüning, who had been Stegerwald's assistant and protege earlier in the 1920s.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] In this role he was both tasked with implementing the government's harsh austerity response to the Great Depression in Germany, which entailed reductions in wages and rolling back labour rights, while also seeking to maintain the welfare state for the millions of unemployed despite harsh cutbacks.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] It was also in this time that he achieved the long-sought for cooperation with the moderate and religious elements of the Protestant right following the secession from the DNVP of the Conservative People's Party and CSVD, who collaborated in the Brüning government.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald remained Labour Minister until the cabinet's dismissal in May 1932.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Following Hitler's appointment as Chancellor in January 1933, Stegerwald was attacked by SA storm troopers at an election rally in Krefeld on 21 February.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] The following month, he helped lead negotiations with the Nazi Party to secure the Centre's support for the Enabling Act of 1933 which handed *de facto* dictatorial power to Hitler.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] From 1933 to 1934 he was indicted, along with Wilhelm Marx and Heinrich Brauns, in the trial of the Cologne *Volksverein Verlag* in his capacity as board member of the National Association for Catholic Germany.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He was on the list of politicians to be purged during the Night of the Long Knives, but received warning and disappeared into exile for three months.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He retired to Franconia during the regime, and in letters to former colleagues urged church leaders to appease the government for fear of the churches' dissolution.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Following the 20 July plot, he was temporarily arrested under the *Aktion Gitter*.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] From August to October 1944 he was detained by the Gestapo in Würzburg prison before being released.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Following the end of the Second World War, the American occupation authority appointed the 71-year-old Stegerwald administrator of the Lower Franconia district.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He became leader of the "Würzburg group" which proved instrumental in the foundation of the Christian Social Union in Bavaria in the late summer and autumn of 1945.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] In Stegerwald's speeches and writing it was clear he considered the new party the fulfillment of his "People's Party" concept of 1920, serving as a "bridge" between denominations, classes, and generations; he coined the name "Christian Social Union".
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Despite the desire of some Catholic labour leaders to found a united labour party with the socialist unions, and of other Catholic leaders to re-found the Centre Party, Stegerwald's model was ultimately taken up nationwide in the form of the Christian Democratic Union of Germany.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Adam Stegerwald died of pneumonia in December 1945.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] He has been honoured extensively, with streets named after him in numerous towns and cities across Germany.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Two political education foundations, the Adam Stegerwald Circle and Stegerwald Foundation, are named in his honour.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] A neighbourhood in Cologne, *Stegerwaldsiedlung*, is also named for him.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Two buildings in Würzburg are named *Adam-Stegerwald-Haus*: the office of the regional CSU branch as well as a student accommodation building.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] Another building in Königswinter, originally acquired by Jakob Kaiser and used by Catholic welfare and political associations in the Weimar period, was renamed *Adam-Stegerwald-Haus* in 1948 after its acquisition by the new German Trade Union Confederation.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adam-stegerwald] After housing a number of different organisations over the decades, the building was sold in 2015 and converted into a nursing home, retaining its name.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] Adelino Fontoura was born in the city of Axixá, in Maranhão, to Antônio Fontoura Chaves and Francisca Dias Fontoura.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] Since childhood, he had a close friendship with the future author Artur Azevedo.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] Moving to Recife, he would work at the satirical journal *Os Xênios*.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] Returning to Maranhão, he initiated his artistical career, performing in a play that would make him arrested.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] After this incident, he moved to Rio de Janeiro.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] He tried the artistic and the journalistic career, failing in the first one.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] He wrote for journals *Folha Nova*, *O Combate* and *A Gazetinha*, where he published some poems and works in prose — and, in this last one, he would collaborate once more with Azevedo, who was its founder.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] After the *Gazeta da Tarde* was bought by José do Patrocínio, Adelino becomes its correspondent in Paris.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] Already very sick, his situation got worse due to the harsh French winter, what made him move to Lisbon in an unsuccessful attempt to get better.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] He died with only 25 years, without publishing any book.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] As mentioned above, Fontoura's work is very sparse, as he did not published anything during his lifetime.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] Attempts of compiling his poetry were made during the 1940s and 1950s by Múcio Leão.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adelino-fontoura] His most well-known poem is the sonnet "Celeste".
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] Filho was born in Itajuípe, Brazil, the son of Adonias Aguiar and Rachel Bastos de Aguiar.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] In 1936, 2 years after finishing high school in Salvador, he moved from the south of Bahia to Rio de Janeiro, Brazil’s capital at the time, where he continued his career in Journalism, previously started in Salvador.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] He worked for well known newspapers such as *Correio da Manhã* and *Revista do Brazil*.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] He was also a literary critic for *Cadernos da "Hora Presente"*, from São Paulo in 1937, *A Manhã*, from 1944 to 1945, along with *Jornal de Letras* (from 1955 to 1960) and *Diário de Notícias* (from 1958 to 1960).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] In São Paulo, he also collaborated with *O Estado de S.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] Between 1946 and 1950, he ran the book publishing company "A Noite".
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] He was the director of the Serviço Nacional de Teatro, in 1954, and director of the Biblioteca Nacional from 1961 to 1971.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] At the same time, he worked for the Agência Nacional at the Ministério da Justiça.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] In 1966, he was elected vice-president of the Associação Brasileira de Imprensa (ABI) and in the following year, he became a member of the Conselho Federal de Cultura (CFC).
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] He was the president of the ABI in 1972 and president of the CFC from 1977 to 1990, when he died.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] As a writer, Adonias Aguiar Filho searched for inspiration for his fiction in the "zona cacaueira" (Cocoa plantations) close to Ilhéus, back to his origins in the South of Bahia, where he was born and raised.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] This ambiance is well displayed in his first novel, *Os servos da morte* (The Servants of Death), published in 1946.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] In the form of the romance novel, reality served as an opportunity to recreate a world charged with symbolism, in the situations as well as in the characters, bearing witness to a tragic sense of life and worldview.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] For his depiction of the characters' inner struggles, he was called by critics "the Brazilian Dostoevsky".
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] He was part of the Grupo Festa, a literary society devoted to spirituality and Catholic tradition.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] The use of original stylistic features, reflective of the internal violence of his characters gave him a fundamental place in the literary generation that created the third phase of Brazilian Modernism in 1945, which was based on a return to more normal disciplines of writing.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] They were concerned about writing with less formal research, while broadening their regional meanings to apply universally.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] Their work still has a significant influence on contemporary Brazilian literature and fiction.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] He was honored with the 21st chair at the Brazilian Academy of Letters (Academia Brasileira de Letras) at the age of 53, May 23, 1969.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] The title was handed to him by his fellow writer from Bahia, Jorge Amado.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] His literary work has been translated into English, German, Spanish, French and Slovak.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] He died in Ilhéus, shortly after his wife did.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/adonias-filho] Fifth holder of the 21st Chair, originally held by Joaquim Serra; elected January 14, 1965.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] In 1928, he converted to Catholicism, eventually becoming head of Catholic Action in Brazil.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] Although initially sympathetic to integralism, he later came to oppose both authoritarianism and fascism, growing into an exponent of Christian democracy in his country.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] He was a vocal critic of the Brazilian military dictatorship.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] Born into a middle-class family in Petrópolis, Lima grew up in the traditional neighborhood of Laranjeiras, in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] He was educated by the private tutor João Köpke, who taught him to read and write, and also received piano lessons from Alberto Nepomuceno.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] Between 1900 and 1909, he traveled through Europe with his family, and upon returning, enrolled at Colégio Pedro II, where he was reported as an ''atheist and Jacobin''.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] In 1913, he graduated from the National Faculty of Law with a degree in Law and Social Sciences.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] In the year of his graduation, Lima travelled to Paris, where he attended lectures by Henri Bergson at the Collège de France.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] As the First World War broke out, he returned to Brazil, where he was appointed to a post at the Itamaraty, but soon left it to assume the management of his family's textile factory.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] In 1919, he began working as a literary critic for *O Jornal*, at a time when he became increasingly close to Catholicism, influenced by his readings of Chesterton and Maritain, as well as by his friendship with the lawyer Jackson de Figueiredo.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] He converted in 1928, under the supervision of Father Leonel Franca.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] Following Jackson de Figueiredo's premature death in 1928, Lima assumed the presidency of Dom Vital Center, then a hub for conservative, anti-communist, anti-liberal, and anti-modernist ideals.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] His involvement in Catholic activism deepened as he became secretary of the Catholic Electoral League, a political activism group, and culminated with his leadership of the Catholic Action in Brazil.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] Lima founded the Universidade Santa Úrsula, located in Rio.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] Alongside Eduardo Frei Montalva, Lima was one of the founders of the Christian Democrat Organization of America.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] He represented Brazil at the Second Vatican Council.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] From 1967 to 1972 he was a member of the Pontifical Council for Justice and Peace.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] Lima had a long career as a professor, teaching Brazilian literature at the National Faculty of Philosophy and at the Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro, which he helped to found.
[src:alceu-amoroso-lima/alceu-amoroso-lima] He also gave lectures on Brazilian culture at the Sorbonne and at the University of New York.
